a gouvenco: I hope you remember the packing press. att least I could wilh
to have moddee made of wood as they are, and how they are made fast
in the ground, thought the moddle should be butt of a foot sguare andmade
in aboue then I shall be able to gett one made here, so lett mee haus either
of them as to the concernes of mr. peeters, I wrott him what was needfull
butt they give no answer besides the 2 billes are not to be found in the house
of the widdow bouwens butt the erecuteurs promised to chearck
for y. they beginnd their sale withim 10 dayes, so that will suply our
customers some what besides next month is our deadest month of the yeare
whoever I'll do all I can that my endeavour may content yd exspectation & sorust
P.S the bills on JPB are found & the heires of the wid bouwens will
deliver them to mee & I'll see them satisfied: they desire that you
please to order them to deliver up to mee the 4 last bales of which 2 arrived
& 2 to come & that their acctt. might be discharged for the valew, which
is well if you be contented, for my part I could advise you toitt, thought
itt be some what against yd adrantidge, because itt will dous preiudicie
in case the goods be sold bij the candle, whoever do, as you please & send yd
in colation in closed my letter, that in case I found any thing to yd preiudicie
then I should detaine itt: all the resting goods which is butt of old stulf will besnd
London Henry Collier
34 maij 1681
S. my last to you was on the 24: curit to which pleased fo be referred sence
rec yd of 15 ditto & accordingly have accepted yd bill for Â£50 st & past to yd
acctt. I must pay mr. Hnnsley about Â£70: s which I could not remitte
him this day att shortsight to rembourse hem where fore I hope you will
don mye the kindeness to pay him said Â£70 st & draw itt on mee att 2 uso
I have the news that Rochus lamere was ordered to come up from
grave jande to London, to give over his carge in English vessels so I supose
that yd bale is like wise reshipt I do advise you to write in yd bills
of loading to be for iyd acctt. & risico, whilst I long to know what pass
remann with - I could wish you could spare yd some in sHenry
to comem over this smmer with mr. Anneslay thathe might see f
any thing were yett to be dow with TH. which is nowere publickley to
be found thought his some is not amonghst the least gentlement
& lives outwardlj like aking
London Arthur Aimeslay
th
Sr. I have before mee yd of 16: curitt you may be confident of the simen
desire I have to do you what service I can & could wish I was able to make
yd mony wort 20 Pord inyeare, butt trade now is to low: yett I hope
you accept of my endeavour, att the latter end of next month shall
send you anecctt: when I hope to cleare the rest I take not ice of the
invoyce & pattarnes yousent of the 2 packes N13 & 14 aboard John winghs
for our acctt in comp. from Exon he is arrived about 6 dayes sence, so
that the goods are dayly exspected: I could not finde any bill this bay
to remitt you for my halfe share att sight, where fore have desired
mr. Colliers that he should pay you Â£70 st which I exspect that he shall
do as soone you receave invoyce & pattarnes, for the rest in ordered please
to send itt mee Ill endeavour to remitt you my share presnntley, that
you might not be in discourse for my acctt the cullours of these
2 bales are indifferent, how the goods shall provs shall advise
you p. next exssoeeting themhere by that time & remaine
London Willamm pnde
th
Antwarp 31 maij 1681
Sr. in answer to yd of 16: curitt do send here inclosed the pattarnes of six
shallones yett resting insold, which I have endeavoured to sell according a
goods now ard butt itt seems I can not make that price for them becauuse
they are of a to dull cullour & to narrow att the latter and of time shall mak
up yd acctt. & if possible cleare yd ballance I could wish I was in a way to doye
better service, then be therto, I have bemable to do & so remaine with kinde
saluter
miy
Antw: P Juny
Amsterdam, De Hulter & van homright
mess. in antwoort aenden ul van 29 pass. sijnde de 30 vatten boter p simon Claes
gearriveert, ende sal voor de selve het beste doen als voor eijgen op 29 hebbe aen ul
geremitteert Â£131:6: op sight ten last guils pelgrom in banco waer voor alh
Â£130: hebbe getaelt & al in rek gedebiteert en wil niet twijffele ofte de selve is ue
wel geworden ul heeft twee balen primo segovische wolle gekoght al hoewel
maer een had geordonneert dat eghter wel is, maer ul hadde behooren volgens ordre
maer een op bredeal te senden want derwaerts maer een noodigh hadde & de rest
herwaerts te senden oversulx wenste peeter Rijns niet was vertroken opdat ul hem
maer een hiede geeft ende vander bale p beurtschip op antwerpen mij toesent
dewelk soo mogelijk is gelieft te affectueren hebbe het monster supera fine
soria segovuna gee gexamineert, de selve animeert eenig sins tot den koop & waert
saeke versekert was dat sall volgens monster soude uytvallen soude wel pertije
begeeven terwijlen op hope van dat succes versoeke uyt die pertije 6 a 8 balen
te doen koopen waer in perticulie kennisse gelieft te gebruyken alsoo het versch
seer veel kan wesen, waert sake onder hant sleght viel soude liever geen begeiren
oversulx tot ul gouverne, renvoye eendeel vant monster waer op gelieft
pre causius te doen letten also vanden in koop onse meeste avantasie dependeert
overso soo dan gelieft in alles te minageeren als voor ejgen en ul antwoort sien
p eerst tegemoet, ende den in koop gedaen sijnde sal wel ul de weirde aenstonts remitt
terwijlen nae groetenisse blijve
wij sijn 2 Juny 1681
hier boven is copie vant geene gisteren met de spaensche brieven heb geschreven, soore ferre
ul aent selve alleenlijk andermael hertelijke recommandeeren die ul debvoor te doen
tot den inkoop vande vermelde 6 a 8 balen soria segoviana van die pertije uyt dew
ul het monster had gesonden ende soo mogelijk is a 30 st te bekomen, dat eghter aen
de gelegentheyt wert gereffeert, het principaelste sijnde dat die wolle maght hebben
volgens monster oock anders geen, en soo die bij tijts bekomen & de selve animeert
sal meerder pertije ordonneeren terwijlen nae cordialee

S. sence I wrot so you on the 27 past non from you, the inclosed for m. Herreford
which now I expers to be to his minde I have disbursed for itt 15 & formerly 24
to have made you debton for 39 st wheve in elces I can seave either him or you
you knew that I am att yd command: I am sorry that I could not remitt you this
day as Ithought doubt lest to have don, so pray be not ostended, butt beleave mee
that I am so straightned, as yet wer I was, whoever that I'll remitt. Â£100- non
& suddainly more whilst I remaine with kinde saluts
